b'<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\n\n\n\n<!DOCTYPE workbook_page PUBLIC " -//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Workbook Page MathML 3.8//EN" "http://oli.web.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_workbook_page_mathml_3_8.dtd">\n<workbook_page id="p3_mole_conversions" xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/"\n    xmlns:bib="http://bibtexml.sf.net/" xmlns:pref="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/preferences/"\n    xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:theme="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/presentation/"\n    xmlns:wb="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/activity/workbook/">\n\n\n    <head>\n        <title>Mole Conversions: Single Step</title>\n        <objref idref="convert_moles"/>\n    </head>\n\n    <body>\n\n        <section id="p3_mole_conversions_DE1">\n            <title>Converting Between Moles and Mass</title>\n            <body>\n                <p>The relationships between formula mass, the mole, and Avogadro\xe2\x80\x99s number can be\n                    applied to compute various quantities that describe the composition of\n                    substances and compounds. For example, if we know the mass and chemical\n                    composition of a substance, we can determine the number of moles and calculate\n                    number of atoms or molecules in the sample. Likewise, if we know the number of\n                    moles of a substance, we can derive the number of atoms or molecules and\n                    calculate the substance\xe2\x80\x99s mass.</p>\n            </body>\n        </section>\n        <section>\n            <title></title>\n            <body>\n\n                <example id="p3_mole_conversions_EX1">\n                    <p>According to nutritional guidelines from the US Department of Agriculture,\n                        the estimated average requirement for dietary potassium is 4.7 g. What is\n                        the estimated average requirement of potassium in moles?</p>\n\n                    <p>The mass of K is provided, and the corresponding amount of K in moles is\n                        requested. Referring to the periodic table, the atomic mass of K is 39.10\n                        amu, and so its molar mass is 39.10 g/mol.</p>\n\n                    <formula>1 mol K = 39.10 g K</formula>\n\n                    <p>We can use this relationship between mol of K and g of K as a conversion\n                        factor and solve using dimensional analysis.</p>\n\n                    <formula>$$\\require{cancel}4.7\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm g\\;\\mathrm\n                        K}\\;\\;\\times\\;\\frac{1\\;\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm K}{39.10\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm\n                        g\\;\\mathrm K}}\\;\\;=\\;\\;0.12\\;\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm K$$</formula>\n\n                    <p>We can see when we set up the dimensional analysis that we will divide by the\n                        molar mass for the answer.</p>\n\n                </example>\n\n                <example id="p3_mole_conversions_EX2">\n                    <p>Vitamin C is a covalent compound with the molecular formula\n                            C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>8</sub>O<sub>6</sub>. The recommended daily dietary\n                        allowance of vitamin C for children aged 4\xe2\x80\x938 years is 1.42\xc3\x9710<sup>\xe2\x88\x924</sup>\n                        mol. What is the mass of this allowance in grams?</p>\n\n                    <p>The moles of C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>8</sub>O<sub>6</sub> is provided, and the\n                        corresponding amount of C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>8</sub>O<sub>6</sub> in grams is\n                        requested. First we will want to calculate the molar mass of the compound\n                            C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>8</sub>O<sub>6</sub>. </p>\n\n\n                    <table>\n                        <tr>\n                            <th>Element</th>\n\n                            <th>Quantity</th>\n\n                            <th/>\n\n                            <th> Molar mass of element</th>\n\n                            <th/>\n\n                            <th>Subtotal</th>\n                        </tr>\n\n                        <tr>\n                            <td>C</td>\n\n                            <td>6</td>\n\n                            <td>x</td>\n\n                            <td>12.01</td>\n\n                            <td>=</td>\n\n                            <td>72.06</td>\n                        </tr>\n\n                        <tr>\n                            <td>H</td>\n\n                            <td>8</td>\n\n                            <td>x</td>\n\n                            <td>1.01</td>\n\n                            <td>=</td>\n\n                            <td>8.08</td>\n                        </tr>\n\n                        <tr>\n                            <td>O</td>\n\n                            <td>6</td>\n\n                            <td>x</td>\n\n                            <td>16.00</td>\n\n                            <td>=</td>\n\n                            <td>96.00</td>\n                        </tr>\n\n                        <tr>\n                            <td align="right" colspan="6"> molar mass = 176.14 g/mol</td>\n                        </tr>\n                    </table>\n\n                    <formula> 1 mol C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>8</sub>O<sub>6</sub> = 176.14 g\n                            C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>8</sub>O<sub>6</sub>\n                    </formula>\n\n                    <p>We can use this relationship between mol of\n                            C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>8</sub>O<sub>6</sub> and g of\n                            C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>8</sub>O<sub>6</sub> as a conversion factor and solve\n                        using dimensional analysis. </p>\n                    <formula>$$\\require{cancel}1.42\\times10^{-4}\\cancel{\\;\\mathrm{mol}\\;{\\mathrm\n                        C}_6{\\mathrm H}_8{\\mathrm O}_6}\\;\\times\\frac{176.14\\;\\mathrm g\\;{\\mathrm\n                        C}_6{\\mathrm H}_8{\\mathrm O}_6}{1\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;{\\mathrm\n                        C}_6{\\mathrm H}_8{\\mathrm O}_6}}\\;=\\;0.0250\\;\\mathrm g\\;{\\mathrm\n                        C}_6{\\mathrm H}_8{\\mathrm O}_6$$</formula>\n\n\n                    <p>We can see when we set up the dimensional analysis that we will multiply by\n                        the molar mass for the answer.</p>\n                </example>\n\n                <image src="../webcontent/mass%20%26%20moles.png"\n                    alt="To convert mass to moles divide by the molar mass and to convert moles to mass multiply by molar mass."/>\n                <composite_activity purpose="learnbydoing">\n                    <p>You find the mass of a sample of sodium chloride with an electronic balance\n                        is 1.22 g. What is this amount in moles?</p>\n                    <p>To make this conversion we will set up the dimensional analysis:</p>\n                    <formula>$$1.22\\;\\mathrm\n                        g\\;\\mathrm{NaCl}\\;\\times\\;\\frac{\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;}{}$$</formula>\n                    <wb:inline idref="salt_conversion_lbd"/>\n                </composite_activity>\n\n                <wb:inline idref="mole_conversion_lbd" purpose="learnbydoing"/>\n            </body>\n        </section>\n\n        <section>\n            <title>Converting Between Moles and Particles</title>\n            <body>\n                <p>In the following examples, we will look at the conversion between moles and\n                    particles (atoms, molecules, or formula units) using Avogadro\'s number, 6.022&times;10<sup>23</sup>.</p>\n                        \n\n                <example id="p3_mole_conversions_EX3">\n                    <p>Copper is commonly used to fabricate electrical wire. How many copper atoms\n                        are in 0.0753 mol of copper wire? </p>\n\n                    <p>The mass of Cu is provided, and the corresponding amount of atoms of Cu is\n                        requested. Based on Avogadro\'s number we know that:</p>\n\n                    <formula> 1 mol Cu = 6.022&times;10<sup>23</sup> atoms Cu</formula>\n\n                    <p>We can use this relationship between mol of Cu and atoms of Cu as a\n                        conversion factor and solve using dimensional analysis.</p>\n                    <formula>$$\\require{cancel}0.0753\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{Cu}}\\;\\times\\;\\frac{\\;6.022\\times10^{23\\;}\\mathrm{atoms}\\;\\mathrm{Cu}}{1\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{Cu}}}\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;=\\;4.53\\times10^{22}$$</formula>\n\n\n                    <p>We can see from the dimensional analysis when converting moles to particles\n                        you multiply by Avogadro\'s number.</p>\n                </example>\n\n                <example id="p3_mole_conversions_EX4">\n                    <p>A sample of water contains 8.4&times;10<sup>22</sup> molecules of water. How many\n                        moles is this? </p>\n\n                    <p>Using Avogadro\'s number we will set up the dimensional analysis.</p>\n                    <formula>$$\\require{cancel}8.4\\times10^{22}\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{molecules}\\;{\\mathrm\n                        H}_2\\mathrm O}\\;\\times\\;\\;\\frac{1\\;\\mathrm{mol}\\;{\\mathrm H}_2\\mathrm\n                        O}{6.022\\times10^{23}\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{molecules}\\;{\\mathrm H}_2\\mathrm\n                        O}}\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;=\\;0.14\\;\\mathrm{mol}\\;{\\mathrm H}_2\\mathrm O$$</formula>\n\n\n\n                    <p>We can see from the dimensional analysis when converting particles to moles\n                        you divide by Avogadro\'s number.</p>\n                </example>\n\n                <image src="../webcontent/moles-particles.png"\n                    alt="When converting from moles to particles, you multiply by Avogadro\'s number. When converting from particles to moles, you divide by Avogadro\'s number."\n                />\n            </body>\n        </section>\n\n        <wb:inline idref="mole_conversion_lbd_2" purpose="learnbydoing"/>\n        <wb:inline idref="mole_conversion_digt" purpose="didigetthis"/>\n\n        <p>Adapted from <link href="https://cnx.org/contents/havxkyvS@9.422:b39avmGq@29/Preface"\n                >Openstax Chemistry</link> under <link\n                href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/"> Creative Commons Attribution\n                4.0 License. </link></p>\n        <p>Download for free at <link\n                href="http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312"\n                >http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312.</link></p>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n    </body>\n</workbook_page>\n'